fields.title: Personality Types
fields.description: The team members discuss to what extend their My Result page fits their personality. This team activity allows for a personalized group discussion of the team’s types and servers as a foundation for all others.

fields.title: Reacting to Scenarios
fields.description: Depending on one’s personality type, team members might react differently to a situation. The team learns from its members’ reactions to several pre-defined scenarios, who could be more different than you would suspect.

fields.title: Pronounced Preferences
fields.description: Through sharing their most pronounced preference out of the four personality type dimensions and that preference’s practical implications, the team members further explore their differences and the impact they have on the team.

fields.title: Team Profile
fields.description: This activity helps the team discover more about its composition as a whole, by zooming in on how the team’s personalities are spread over the four personality type dimensions. The team members learn how their personal preferences help shape team profile.

fields.title: Team Meetings
fields.description: The team’s personality type preferences impact its meetings. The team has a conversation about the level of structure and behavior that is appropriate in their meetings, after discussing how its personality types desire certain behaviors and processes.

fields.title: Speed Dates
fields.description: In a series of ‘speed dates’, the team members talk to each other about their interpersonal comparison reports, which helps them better understand one another and learn more about each other’s types.

fields.title: Strengths and Challenges
fields.description: With each personality type come certain skills that come naturally to a person with that type, and the same is true for challenges. The participants highlight a several of these which helps them learn more about each other’s’ strengths and limitations.

fields.title: Capitalize on Strength
fields.description: Depending on your personality, some workplace tasks give you less stress than others. In this activity, the team evaluates how its tasks are divided among its members, and might decide on some changes that reduce stress and increase productivity.

fields.title: Design your Team Manifesto
fields.description: How would you like your team to act when making decisions, participating in a meeting, faced with conflict or when you communicate? It’s time to create together your unique team manifesto – the written set of behaviors that will transform your teamwork.

Ask <COWORKERNAME/> to help keep you on task, but don’t be afraid to challenge their assumptions about existing procedures if you have an idea that could work better.

In your work, you probably focus on the big picture over small details and tend to be open to midstream changes and adaptations. In fact, at times you may be so open to exciting new possibilities that you struggle to see projects through to the end. <COWORKERNAME/> may also like to go wherever the project leads, changing directions fluidly and adapting to new and better ways of doing things. But, preferring to focus on the concrete, <COWORKERNAME/> may have trouble completely embracing your more abstract ideas. In turn, you may lose patience with <COWORKERNAME/>’s experimental processes and may be on to the next thing before they are ready to move forward.

When working together, set measurable goals at the beginning of the project and hold each other accountable for sticking with them. Leverage your ability to see things from multiple perspectives to help <COWORKERNAME/> cut down on the time they would otherwise need to devote to experimentation. Be ready to provide concrete examples of the concepts you envision, and ask for input from more procedurally-minded colleagues if needed.

You tend to bring an open-minded and innovative approach to your work and likely have a talent for seeing the big picture. But this can sometimes come at the cost of seeing projects through to the end. While it’s important to both you and <COWORKERNAME/> to understand the essence of tasks, <COWORKERNAME/> may spend additional time finessing the details and trying to get things right, whereas you may feel more eager to move on to something new. You may at times feel constrained by the plans <COWORKERNAME/> wants to put in place, while, <COWORKERNAME/> may sometimes think that you get too distracted and need to be more focused on the end result.

When working on a project together, be prepared to answer detailed questions about new ideas you introduce, even if they are still in the incubation phase. Tap <COWORKERNAME/>’s planning tendencies to chart a more defined course than you would otherwise set while using your ability to see things from multiple perspectives to help them achieve a fuller understanding of the project.

Like you, <COWORKERNAME/> is an imaginative thinker who focuses on the big picture, sometimes at the expense of the details. You’re both comfortable with rapid- fire changes of direction and probably like to have a lot of irons in the fire at once. While you may fuel each other’s innovation and generate great ideas, when working together, the two of you may, at times, have difficulty discerning whether your ideas are doable or sticking to a mandated schedule.

To avoid stumbling blocks when working on a project with <COWORKERNAME/>, set deadlines at the beginning and hold each other accountable for meeting them. Prioritize your tasks and focus on the most important ones, even if a shiny new idea starts to tug at your attention midway though. And if needed, run your ideas by more detail-oriented colleagues to get a sense of what issues may arise in the implementation phase.

fields.name: Mentor
fields.text:
<NAME/>, because you are an ENFJ, you use your empathy, excellent communication skills, enthusiasm, and warmth to gain cooperation in the organization. With your basic attitude of credulity and idealism, you likely see the good and the human potential in everyone, and you enjoy drawing out the best in people.

Most likely, you relentlessly pursue high ideals, often humanitarian and people-focused. Sometimes you may gloss over or ignore the “dark side,” preferring to anticipate the positive instead of the negative. You may be disappointed when reality doesn’t measure up to your high expectations for human potential.

Placing a high value on the ethical and moral, you probably want fairness for all, and you have a never-ending desire to make work meaningful. At times, your enthusiasm is dramatically demonstrated with effusive expressions of intense emotion. Your impulsive, dramatic flair is yet another way to heighten the overall awareness of issues that you consider crucial.

Like other ENFJs, you have a high need for developing empathic relationships. These must be deep and meaningful to satisfy your intense desire for rapport. If not given the opportunity to have meaningful relationships, you may become stressed and have difficulties on the job. Since you are so responsive to others, you may lose sight of your own needs or get stuck in the middle of opposing forces. You abhor a lack of caring. For you, an organization exists to enable people to perform—not the other way around.

Integrity is the hallmark of your relationships. You tend to be authentic and as true to your values as possible. Since you want to avoid being phony, you may resist assignments that require some pretense. Being cast into a role that downplays authenticity may cause you all kinds of grief. Therefore, it’s probably difficult for people to talk you into doing something that’s against your better judgment.

When you focus your attention on someone else, your listening skills probably come out second to none. You not only listen, you hear much of what is not said.  Sensitive to nuances and unspoken aspects of communication, you have an unusual capacity to understand other people’s viewpoints. Most likely, you have a sixth sense for how to optimize a conversation and interact with just about anyone. The greater the number and range of people you are able to get to know, the happier you are.

You tend to find meaning and significance in even the smallest event. Because you are able to make connections between seemingly different things, you may often make inferences that most people miss. Therefore, you tend to know what flows together and what does not, though at times, you may be at a loss in explaining the specifics of “why.” Finding meaning and philosophizing probably brings you great joy, and you may tremendously appreciate a good discussion on just about anything, as long as it does not turn sour or unfriendly.

<NAME/>, like others with the ENFJ type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your empathy, cooperative spirit, warmth, graciousness, and keen listening and communication skills. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: ENFJs are natural communicators, warmly enthusiastic, popular and sociable, responsive, responsible, and have a charismatic charm.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ENFJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ENFJs, you tend to be very idealistic, and you may find it surprising when someone doesn’t share or, worse yet, violates your principles. When this happens, you’re much more likely to feel pity rather than anger toward the individual at fault. You see things as they should be in a perfect world, so it may be quite difficult for you to accept your and others’ limitations. Consequently, you may have a fluctuating self-image as you struggle to live up to your own ideals. 

Furthermore, you may often find yourself taking on others’ troubles as your own, as long as their troubles aren’t in violation of your core values. When you have empathy for another, you may become overly involved in fixing the person’s problems and stretch yourself too thin. At times, you may be seen as agreeing with each person you relate to and get stuck between opposing forces. However, you avoid conflict and hurting people’s feelings. This may mean holding on to unworthy relationships and turning a blind eye to character flaws that undermine your idea of someone. 

Finally, such empathy also gives way to sensitivity, particularly to criticism. You respond well to praise, but you may be deeply hurt by disapproval. And, if you become overly flustered or upset, you may be prone to anger or overreacting in a seemingly irrational manner.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

ENFJs may sometimes be dubbed as “meddling” or “busybodies,” which isn’t the case at all. It’s true that you enjoy having deep conversations with others, often drawing out personal information. But your objective isn’t to pry. You’re genuinely interested in what others have to say, and you truly want to help people solve their problems. In fact, it’s hard for you to stay impassive to someone else’s plight. That said, you’re very perceptive and know when it’s best to respect another person’s need for space or privacy. 

At the extreme, people may also think of ENFJs as being “overly dramatic.” Partly, this may be a misinterpretation based on your delivery. You can be very effusive in the way you express yourself, and those who are more straight-faced may think you’re being over-the-top when you’re really just trying to bring awareness to an issue. And while you likely have very strong feelings about a lot of things, you tend to keep your opinions to yourself, especially if bringing them up would be upsetting to your company.

fields.name: Motivator
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ESFP, you’re enthusiastic, have a way of encouraging those around you, and draw energy through interactions with other people. Those in the workplace most likely appreciate the liveliness that you bring to group settings. When interacting with others, you probably have no problem sharing freely and openly. Because being around others is important to you, one of the greatest passions in your life is most likely being surrounded by a lively group of friends. 

You’re dynamic and have a knack for improvising. Within the workplace, you probably thrive in environments that provide a lot of variety. As such, you have an ability to balance projects and can not only get lost in the moment while working on a project but can also bounce around a lot, tackling different projects throughout the day. Compared to others, you are likely open to new opportunities and have a willingness to jump right in. Others in your workplace most likely see you as flexible and adaptable with a desire to keep your options open.

<NAME/>, you rely on personal and value-based judgments. In conversations with others, you are likely to stick to your values, and your coworkers probably appreciate the conviction that you have. When interacting with others or presenting your ideas to a group, you most likely speak with authority and confidence. As such, when your values are challenged, you’re unlikely to waver or falter. 

Similar to other ESFPs, you care deeply about other people’s feelings. Therefore, you probably don’t have a problem serving as a counselor and are usually willing to help those around you. With others, you likely do a good job balancing both listening and talking. In a similar vein, you may not be afraid to ask for help or to rely on others. Generally speaking, you are curious about other people and likely have a keen eye for noticing when something is bothering them. 

 When interacting with others, you probably want to be able to express yourself. As such, you may have a tendency to speak first and then think later. Additionally, you may bounce from topic to topic. While being a fun conversationalist, your communication style may take you and others on wild tangents. You also likely want to be in the know and, as a consequence, you probably don’t mind indulging in gossip from time to time

Given your enthusiastic and bold nature, you’re probably not afraid to take social chances, willingly throwing yourself into new situations and putting yourself out there. Similarly, you may go out of your way to meet and welcome new people. In these settings, you probably not only talk about your experiences and share your feelings but you likely do a great job of digging to find out more about people.

<NAME/>, as an ESFP, you are enthusiastic, dynamic, bold, and open to improvisation. In the workplace, your coworkers likely value your energy and passion, your willingness to speak up, and your ability to go with the flow .You are accommodating and encouraging in the workplace, and people probably value the connections you willingly form with them.
fields.text_short: ESFPs are hands-on operators, able to “smell the roses,” natural negotiators, the life of the party, a lot of fun, and make for exciting company.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ESFP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ESFPs, you are fun-loving and social. Yet, you’re often so busy enjoying life that your other responsibilities may suffer, and you may frequently show up unprepared. Because you’re a master at improvisation, this may not upset you as much as it does the people around you. You’re savvy about taking shortcuts and making quick fixes, while sticking with long-range plans and repairs is probably not your cup of tea. At times, you may find that you’ve pulled together a masterpiece in the nick of time, but that it later falls apart at the seams. 

Furthermore, with an insatiable hunger for spontaneity, you may sometimes be considered rather irresponsible, especially in a very structured work environment. You’re not much for planning. It’s not that you forget to plan; you really just don’t like it. As a consequence, you may need to be reminded to meet deadlines and finish projects. 

Finally, you are warmhearted and generous. You truly love people, and you tend to value your friends so much that you may turn a blind eye to their negative behaviors and interpersonal conflicts. Being exceptionally generous, you may impulsively give too much of your time and possessions alike. In the end, you may wind-up neglecting your own well-being.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

ESFPs may sometimes be seen as “superficial” since they tend to appreciate lighthearted fun and beauty. Indeed, you are drawn to the aesthetically pleasing, so you probably have good taste and fine possessions, and you’re likely up on the latest and greatest. But you also have sincere depth, especially when it comes to interpersonal relationships. And, while you tend to brush unpleasantness aside, it isn’t because you’re one-dimensional or flippant. It’s because you have such zest for life and tend to live for today, possessing a strong desire to make the most of any situation. 

At times, ESFPs may come across to some as “selfish,” which isn’t the case at all. This may be because you tend to act on your impulses, steal the spotlight, and indulge in what you find most enjoyable. Such behavior may seem self-serving, especially to someone who doesn’t know you well. However, you are actually very generous, freely giving of your time and energy. Indeed, your approach to life in general may be very egalitarian, the headline being, “what’s mine is yours.” While you may often be the center of attention, it’s not due to egotism or for the purpose of self-promotion. Rather, it’s your wish to entertain and please others. To you, life is a bowl of cherries, and you want everyone else to see it that way, too.

fields.name: Harmonizer
fields.text:
<NAME/>, because you are an INFP, you tend to be very supporting of others and may relate and dedicate yourself to a few special people. And, with a quiet enthusiasm, you may often become the advocate and champion of causes, caring deeply about your goals and aspirations.

Your values tend to revolve around the ethical and moral, wanting goodness—the “greater good”—for all. Whatever you decide to favor tends to be very carefully selected and, as a result, be both highly personal and very deeply felt. Over time, the values you select may become the core of your identity. While you are usually agreeable and flexible, if anything happens that violates your ideals, you will probably stand your ground. Anyone trying to manipulate you is likely to meet a silent, determined, and unbending wall of resistance.

Patient with complicated situations, you are capable of intense concentration and dedication. You tend to work in creative bursts of energy, placing an intense focus on projects that you’re passionate about. Consequently, you may become so absorbed in your efforts that you neglect your own needs.

Like other INFPs, you are naturally tuned in to the emotions and motivations of others. You are likely gifted at understanding individual differences and observing sentiments that are important to others. In fact, you probably have a greater awareness of other people’s emotions than you are even able to verbalize. Since you may naturally become concerned with the personal problems of your coworkers, you may feel a sense of obligation in resolving grievances, conflicts, and disagreements, however small.

While you aren’t prone to effusive expressions of emotion, you are likely brimming with enthusiasm and conviction beneath the surface. Your deep feelings are usually hidden by a quiet reserve. Since you strive for perfection in verbal expression, you may sometimes have difficulty communicating the intensity of what you feel. While you can comfortably learn to speak up, one of your greatest gifts tends to be reflected in non-verbal communication skills. Therefore, you may find written communication a more rewarding and precise outlet for your skilled use of image and metaphor.

Because you enjoy variety in what you do, you are frequently drawn to many new projects, ideas, and changing activities. At times, you may become fragmented from wanting to do too many things or from being pulled in too many directions.

You are usually content to work alone, savoring solitude for contemplation while making significant contributions. Still, you tend to be a very cooperative team player. If you are asked to collaborate, you would prefer for it to be one-on-one or in small groups, allowing you to relate to others at a deeper level. Interacting in large groups of people can sap you of your energy, so you may find it to be counterproductive.

<NAME/>, like others with the INFP type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your ability to develop strong empathic relationships, your genuine sensitivity to the needs of others, and your devotion to values and ethics. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: INFPs are peacekeepers, deeply caring, idea oriented, undertake a great deal, and get absorbed in projects.
fields.blind_spots:
As an INFP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other INFPs, you tend to be very idealistic, often setting yourself up for disappointment when you realize time and again that no one and nothing is perfect. You tend to be a big-picture thinker, having a clear sense of how something holistically feels and overlooking its individual parts. You feel quite strongly about things, so much so that you may refuse to consider contradicting facts, data, or opinions.  

Furthermore, you tend to have high standards, particularly for yourself, and you may be your strongest critic. You’re slow to give yourself credit when things go right and quite hard on yourself when they don’t. You probably feel a lot of insecurity and may require a lot of praise. Consequently, criticism and critiques may be very difficult for you to swallow. 

Finally, since you tend to be private and reserved, it may be difficult for others to get to know you. You might be touchy about having your personal space invaded, and you may feel self-conscious or awkward expressing your feelings. However, you often feel guilty about not giving more of yourself as you strive to please everyone. It’s quite difficult for you to take an opposing stance on an issue, so people may wind up thinking you agree with an idea or decision when you’re really just harboring an unpopular opinion.
fields.misunderstood:

We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Some people may think that INFPs are “illogical” or “irrational” when this isn’t the case at all. It’s true that you may often be led by your heart, relying heavily on your and others’ emotions to guide you. In fact, you have such strong empathy that you can often feel what others feel. However, this doesn’t mean you are incapable of using logic or that your sensitivity can be equated with foolishness. On the contrary, you excel at making sense of subjective material, and you are completely capable of setting sentiment aside when it is right to do so. 

INFPs are also sometimes dubbed “indecisive” or “noncommittal.” This may be because you take your time making important decisions and want to stay open to new information as long as possible. Generally, you consider all sides of an issue, paying close attention to the impact it will have on yourself and others, with the stronger priority usually being on others. You likely spend lots of time gathering everyone’s opinions and weighing the pros and cons so that in the end, you can feel confident that you’ve made the best decision for everyone involved. You aren’t indecisive; you’re just careful. And once you’ve committed to a cause or course of action, you tend to be fiercely loyal to it.

fields.name: Developer
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an INFJ, you are insightful, devoted, and compassionate. You likely think deeply about projects to ensure that you have an accurate and thorough understanding. Whether working on a project or working with another person, you probably have a deep sense of responsibility to live up to your commitments. You also don’t mind helping people work through personal issues and are committed to treating everyone fairly. 

 You put your best efforts into your work on a regular basis and have a quiet determination, stemming from your desire to find meaning in your work. Because of these tendencies, however, you may feel yourself burning out more often than you’d like. You also may have a hard time saying no. In fact, there may be times when you feel like you want to just disappear, escaping from all of the demands you’ve put on yourself.

 <NAME/>, you probably set high and idealistic standards for yourself and feel an intense responsibility to live up to these standards. Likewise, you may hold a deep desire to not disappoint others. As such, you probably find it very stressful when someone is upset with you or when you can’t help them. And because your standards are so high, you may sometimes question yourself or underestimate your abilities. 

 Your colleagues probably recognize that you’re a good listener and demonstrate a clear compassion for others. And because you have a knack for thinking conceptually about people-problems, you can often provide insights that would otherwise never occur to them. Further, since you likely have a democratic nature, you are inclined to see that others are treated equally and fairly. In a similar vein, you go out of your way to avoid conflict and probably find yourself being accommodating even of people you don’t really care for.

 You may not always speak up for what you need or indicate when your needs are not being met. For one, you likely have trouble communicating the complexity and intensity of your needs and feelings. Additionally, you are most likely particularly sensitive to criticism and are, therefore, more apt to put the needs of other people ahead of your own. Harmony within the workplace is a key value for you.

 Given your concern for others, the focus of your work is likely on the common good rather than self-serving motives. Your interpersonal responsibility keeps you committed to your organization and your colleagues. 

 <NAME/>, like others with the INFJ type, you have a devotion to your work as well as to the people you work with. Your high standards benefit you and others. Your deep compassion and care for those around you as well as the insightful contributions that you bring to projects are characteristics that are most likely valued by others within your workplace.
fields.text_short: INFJs are quietly forceful, concerned for others, utilize single-minded concentration, serve the common good, and put their best effort into work.
fields.blind_spots:
As an INFJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other INFJs, you tend to be very private. In fact, even those closest to you may not know the “real” you. You often present yourself differently depending on the situation, revealing yourself as a picture of who you think you should be in front of certain people. You’re extremely protective of yourself, so you’ll disclose bits and pieces of your life as you see fit. Consequently, people may think you’re hard to get to know and difficult to understand. 

Furthermore, you tend to be very idealistic and may function with a sort of tunnel vision when it comes to your own values. You’re often so convinced you’re right about things that you may ignore contradictions and dismiss differing opinions right off the bat. And, since you tend to be a perfectionist in pursuit of your ideals, you may seldom feel internal peace, often worrying that you fall short of your full potential. 

Finally, it’s likely very upsetting to you if someone questions your motives or disparages your principles. Even if there is validity in a criticism, your stubborn streak may obstruct any sort of change. Indeed, once your mind is made up, you’ll steadfastly hold to your stance. Still, you very much dislike conflict and may internalize negative feelings, leaving you with lasting anger and resentment.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Being dubbed “shy” or “reclusive” may be ways INFJs are misperceived. Some people may equate your quiet nature with discomfort in social situations. However, often times you’re just not very interested in small talk or shallow interactions. You don’t see the value in making idle chit-chat when you could be having a more meaningful conversation about topics that actually matter to you. It takes energy for you to be around others, so if you’re going to expend some of it, you’d rather it be for real enjoyment or a purpose. That said, when do you have deep, meaningful interactions, you truly value them. 

INFJs may also be perceived as “secretive,” when that’s not the case at all. You probably don’t often reveal a lot about yourself, especially with people you don’t know well or without prompting. But this isn’t because you’re hiding something or against sharing. You just don’t like broadcasting your feelings. Furthermore, you tend to be very modest and don’t assume that others are itching to hear all about you. You’re not one to seek center stage, but if someone shows interest in getting to know you, you’ll likely open up.

fields.name: Planner
fields.text:
<NAME/>, because you are an ISTJ, you are always inspecting, looking for discrepancies and omissions. You are probably excellent at comparing a performance or product to a standard and do so with rare thoroughness. Since you tend to quickly register when something is out of place, you may often notice deviations that others overlook.

Most likely, you tend to approach situations in a linear and step-by-step fashion, rather than processing several things at once and in no particular sequence. Some environments, where things happen on many different levels at one time, may be stressful for you.

While you don’t usually take the first step in defining relationships and bringing people together, a sense of belonging is probably important to you. You also want to preserve traditions and appreciate the value of rituals, ceremonies, and celebrations in providing a sense of permanence in the organization. In fact, if there is an absence of traditions, you may be the one to create them.

Like other ISTJs, you want an orderly, stable work environment where your tasks are clearly defined. It’s probably important to you to have a sense that life and business will go on as usual in a predictable, constant sort of way. To that end, you tend to be efficient and prefer things to be on time and on schedule. You likely keep a routine and work with steady energy, and you may lose patience with people who do not operate this way.

Being responsible is also very important to you since it is a pathway to stability. Not only do you thrive on responsibility, you rarely turn down opportunities to take on more. In fact, you may have trouble saying no and end up overloaded. Furthermore, it may be difficult for you to delegate any of your work unless you have a great deal of confidence that the other person will complete the task according to your standards.

It’s also crucial to your sense of stability that your organization thrive, so you can be counted on to complete all assignments and follow through. To be sure that the goal is achieved, you tend to be cooperative, as long as the interest of the organization is at heart. Because you are so dedicated to getting the job done and tend to be loyal to your team, you may even undertake tasks that no one else wants to do for the good of the team.

You probably have a capacity for attention to detail and gathering facts. Most likely, you can handle complex figures and make sense out of them with ease. Since you tend to excel at measurement, you have an ability to accurately budget or allocate quantities and tend to be skilled at anything having to do with logistics. Getting things to the right place at the right time and in the right quantity may be something you’re naturally good at.

<NAME/>, like others with the ISTJ type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your steadiness, dependability, loyalty, dedication, and talent for observation and inspection. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: ISTJs are serious and quiet, “no-nonsense,” task-oriented, responsible and trustworthy, and will see a job through to the end.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ISTJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ISTJs, you have a strong belief in right and wrong. To you, facts are facts, and you may not have much respect for people who ignore or are ignorant of them. You expect people to be logical, too, in much the same way as you are. Others may view such an objective stance as impersonal and cold. At the same time, since you are so detailed and rely so heavily on evidential proof, it may be difficult for you to accept when you’ve made a mistake, and you may be particularly hard on yourself for it. 

Furthermore, you like to do things by the book and may be unwilling to bend the rules, even if it could benefit the situation or the people involved. You believe that policies and regulations are in place for a reason, to the point where you may not be responsive to the need for change. Moreover, there may be times when you’d rather not learn new procedures, having mastered the ones you are accustomed to. 

Finally, you are eager for responsibility and, at times, you may take on too much. It may be difficult for you to say no, causing you to become overloaded. When this happens, you’re unlikely to ask for help or pass your tasks to someone else since you may believe you’re the only one who can finish the work reliably.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Sometimes, ISTJs may come across as “unsympathetic” or “disinterested.” It’s true that you have a low need to express yourself and tend to be a private person, but you also have very strong social skills. However, in situations where emotions run high, you’re unlikely to communicate any sentiments that would make you vulnerable. What others don’t know is how much you are feeling and thinking on the inside, but it’s your steady appearance and sense of composure that can lead others to question your empathy. Since you may not always pick up on people’s feelings, you may not realize that they are looking for you to reveal the compassion you feel but keep to yourself. 

Being “overly structured” or “rigid” is another misconception some people may have about ISTJs. It’s likely you believe in procedure, but this doesn’t mean that you’re rigid. You respect tried-and-true methods and guidelines. If they’ve worked before, you know they’ll work again, which can help you get the job done without wasting any time. And while deviating from familiar standards probably isn’t the norm for you, you’re able to recognize when change is necessary.

fields.name: Mobilizer
fields.text:
<NAME/>, because you are an ENTJ, you naturally take charge, whether of people or your own success. You tend to be a visionary and enjoy planning for your team’s future. You are happiest when you are taking action to realize a lofty goal or grand vision, which you may take a large role in designing. 

Most likely, you love problem-solving, and, if not given problems to solve, you will likely find or create them to satisfy this need. Not surprisingly, you are not typically a day-to-day routine operator, and you may easily become bored if your imagination is not inspired.

Like other ENTJs, you prefer to take the initiative rather than waiting to see what happens and then responding. In fact, your need for action can be so strong, sometimes you may need to tie yourself to a chair to allow for the kind of deliberation and research required to make a decision. If more reflective people try to slow down your pace, you may become frustrated.

Even though you prefer to be in charge, you can be a team player when it makes sense, but you will quickly abandon that tack if you believe it is no longer efficient. In fact, inefficiency may be one of your biggest pet peeves. At times, this preference can come across in a terse communication style, and you may become impatient if people need you to explain yourself. 

Though you love competition, you’re not necessarily focused on winning; you may enjoy the process more than the end result. Still, you have a high need for achievement and a, perhaps hidden, fear of failure. You can be your own biggest critic, so when you receive feedback that is delivered logically and objectively, you are likely to take it well. 

You don’t necessarily grant people authority based on their status, but rather expect them to prove themselves capable. In fact, logic and reasoning factor into almost everything you do and how you relate to others. If someone cannot give you a compelling rationale for a course of action, you are likely to reject it or, better yet, you may jump in and try to design a better solution.

Because you place a higher premium on thinking than feeling, you may not always take care of your or others’ emotions. In a work context, you don’t really like it when others rely on emotions to help make decisions. You prefer to keep discussions on a logical, rational track. However, not allowing others to be expressive, at times, can lead to the very emotional outbursts that you are trying to avoid. Even so, you can be a keen judge of character, often quickly and accurately sizing up people you meet. 

<NAME/>, like others with the ENTJ type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your natural leadership and take-charge approach, your visionary and big-picture thinking, and your commitment to getting things done better and faster. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: ENTJs are frank and decisive, natural leaders who think on their feet, confident, and well-informed.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ENTJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ENTJs, you have a “take charge” attitude and tend to energetically pursue your goals. However, you can become quite stubborn, perhaps even ruthless at times, in this pursuit. If someone suggests an objective that is contrary to your own, you may become argumentative and insist on winning. Even if there is merit in the opposing view, you’ll likely find ways to criticize it and steadfastly dig in your heels. 

Furthermore, you want to cut to the chase so you can reach your goals quickly. This may lead you to make hasty decisions without considering all sides of an issue. You may also be impatient with people who require more time to reflect before coming to conclusions. You want to just “get on with it” and may mistakenly attribute such deliberations to ignorance or disinterest. 

Finally, you may not be very adept at understanding other people’s feelings, or expressing your own. You tend to be tough and blunt, which can sometimes bleed into insensitivity and hurt the people around you. You tend to bottle up your emotions, but at some point, they may erupt in explosive outbursts. This may happen when you’re under stress or feeling criticized, but it may come across to others as an overreaction to the situation.

We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Some people may misperceive ENTJs as “unfriendly.” This may be because you tend to be very task-oriented at work and don’t see it as a place to get chummy. In reality, you likely love making friends just as much as the next person, but you would probably prefer to focus on your responsibilities instead of chit-chatting when there’s work to be done. 

Being dubbed as “arrogant” and “narrow-minded” may also be ways that ENTJs are misperceived. It’s true that you push hard for your opinions and are very confident, but you also value feedback and willingly take it to heart, especially when confronted with logical, well-thought-through opinions. Even so, you’re willing to critique and refute those opinions, not for egotistical purposes, but in the interest of finding truth and success.

fields.name: Composer
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ISFP, broadly speaking, you are observant, resourceful, and adaptive. As such, you have a willingness to attend to others as well as an ability to pick up when something is wrong with another person. Additionally, you can likely improvise when working on projects and, compared to other people, you’d probably rather keep things open and flexible than have them planned and settled. 

You have a go-with-the-flow approach to your work, greatly valuing the freedom to explore as needed. When necessary, though, you can adapt to your circumstances and meet the set guidelines. Given your desire for open-endedness, at times, you may have difficulties with inertia or getting going on projects. You’d rather take each day as it comes than plan thoroughly for the future.

<NAME/>, you probably don’t like to work within tight restraints and you may instinctively want to push back when there is too much structure. However, you likely won’t resist too much because harmony is also important to you. Overall, you are adaptable and, therefore, are open to making the necessary adjustments. And because you don’t want to make a fuss, you will most likely find your own way of doing things within a system.

Your coworkers probably recognize you as warm and friendly, which is typical of ISFPs. You are accepting of people and their preferences. As such, you care about others and you don’t mind listening to what others have to say. Additionally, you’re probably quick to deflect compliments and, therefore, your colleagues may see you as humble. Overall, you are interpersonally sensitive and attuned to others, which may make others more comfortable.

Despite your openness to people, you appreciate time alone. At times, you may come across as both quiet and reserved. While you are usually willing to listen, you don’t have a strong need to be verbally expressive. Although you care deeply about people’s feelings, you like to have the time and space to privately recharge. Given these tendencies, others may perceive you as mellow, at least on the surface. 

When approaching work or your daily life, you probably have a tendency to make adjustments to help you fit in. Again, for you, creating harmony is more important than having other people attend to your needs. You are willing to go where the winds carry you, likely making the assumption that it is easier to simply adjust than attempt to shape the environment you are in. 

<NAME/>, like others with the ISFP type, you bring an openness and adaptability to the workplace. You are probably a free spirit, willing to improvise and live in the moment. The supportive ear that you provide others is likely appreciated. These traits are most likely valued by both your coworkers and the organization.
fields.text_short: ISFPs are quietly friendly and warm, loyal followers, free spirits, modest about their abilities, and guided by values.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ISFP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ISFPs, you tend to be unusually generous, to the point where you will often put the needs of others above your own. Also, you tend to be very trusting of people, rarely issuing much skepticism or considering such things as ulterior motives. Because of this, you may wind up being taken advantage of by people less scrupulous than yourself. 

Furthermore, you like having cooperative, genuine relationships with people, and you may be very sensitive to what others think of you. Criticism of any kind may be very difficult for you to swallow, leaving you to lose confidence or feel rejected. At times, you may think you’re being criticized even when it’s not intended. Your self-value is tied so much to others’ opinions that you can be quite hard on yourself without much warrant. 

Finally, you tend to be very independent and prefer not to have a lot of structure or rules. Being quite “carefree,” you’re not much for planning or long-term commitments, and such unpredictability may leave others wondering if they can count on you. In fact, you live so much in the moment that you may miss the broader view or scope of things.
fields.misunderstood:

We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

ISFPs are sometimes misperceived as having “suspicious” motives. Actually, you’re quite easygoing and extemporaneous, but such lack of intention may be misinterpreted, especially by very skeptical people. Because you’re quietly persuasive and quick to redirect a crisis, it may seem that you’ve got a hidden agenda. But really, you just want to minimize uncomfortable situations and make the most of the moment. 

At the extreme, ISFPs may come across as “lazy,” which isn’t the case at all. This may be because you appreciate comfort and tend to perform at a moderate pace. Furthermore, you may not be very expressive about the work you do, often remaining outwardly calm and cool. To some, this may be interpreted as your being blasé or unambitious, but really, you’re just able to stay relaxed about completing your tasks. In fact, you put a great deal of energy into the work you do, especially when you believe in it.

fields.name: Strategist
fields.text: , because you are an INTJ, you are a naturally conceptual thinker. You thrive when implementing strategies and solving complex problems, and you tend to be especially skilled at anticipating the ripple effects of a plan. Most likely, you can both build theoretical models and translate theory into practice, and you tend to be good at putting together the big picture using the applicable parts. Though you enjoy developing systems, you’d rather leave the execution and routine to others. You have an uncanny ability to predict and anticipate outcomes, which can sometimes come to you in moments of deep reflection. You appreciate when others allow this process to take place rather than pushing you to make quick decisions. This is not to say that you don’t have a sense of urgency or lose sight of the goal. In fact, you can be very task-oriented, sometimes even to the point of obsession. Most likely, you prefer to make decisions carefully, focusing on the goals and the vision of where the team is going. You are probably keenly aware of the inner workings of the whole organization and its various subsystems. Above all, you trust your ability to rely on logic in any decision-making situation. Like other INTJs, your natural skepticism is evident in your tendency to ask why and question the status quo. You don’t favor following routines, standard operating procedures, or going by the book. In fact, you are constantly evaluating and reevaluating to determine if something can be done better. Most of your analysis happens internally, and you don’t tend to over-communicate. At times, this may cause you to come across to others as mysterious or secretive. In your mind, you’re being efficient in your communication style, which you value in others as well. In fact, when people tend to speak at length or become wordy, you may tune them out. You are comfortable giving people directions about tasks and providing structure in a work context, but you may be less comfortable taking the initiative in striking up friendships. This means that you may be slow to develop relationships, and you may have fewer, deeper bonds rather than many casual acquaintances. Like others with a preference for thinking rather than feeling, you may seem cool and aloof at times, and you may not always take care of your or others’ emotions. In a work context, you might not really like it when others rely on emotions to help make decisions. You prefer for discussions to be resolved logically and objectively. , like others with the INTJ type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your ability to anticipate and predict outcomes, your knack for seeing the forest and the trees, and your ability to develop complex systems and designs. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: INTJs are original thinkers, naturally high achievers, interested and innovative, unimpressed with authority, and focus with single-minded concentration.
fields.blind_spots:
As an INTJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other INTJs, you tend to have strong faith in your own ideas, sometimes missing the weaknesses in them. You’re very independent and can be single-minded. Having such confidence in your philosophies and designs, you may see little reason to solicit input and suggestions, and you may be quite prickly when criticized.  And while you probably don’t intend to be arrogant or a know-it-all, you may sometimes come across that way. 

Furthermore, you tend to be quite demanding of yourself and others. Being very analytical and prone to perfectionism, you may impose standards that are unrealistically high. If someone comes across as illogical or doesn’t measure up in some way, you may be quick to judge and forthright in expressing your distaste. 

Finally, you may find too much structure or bureaucracy frustrating. You’re not one to carelessly accept what you see as useless paperwork or protocol. And, if you can poke holes in the red tape, you’ll likely find ways to underhandedly or subtly communicate your frustration to those in authority.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

At times, INTJs may be seen as acting “superior” or “arrogant.” It’s true that you may not often look to others for advice or suggestions, but that’s only because you are confident in the work you’ve done. Your straightforward and logical communication style may further contribute to this misconception. However, it isn’t really that you think you’re smarter or better than everyone else. You just want things to run smoothly and you’re not one to beat around the bush. So, you’re usually upfront with your opinions and reservations, often quite matter-of-factly, but for the sake of logic and efficiency. 

People also sometimes misperceive INTJs as “detached.” You’re a quiet, private individual, but that doesn’t mean that you don’t value relationships or feel sincere compassion for those around you. You have deep affection for others; you just don’t feel the need to express it. And while you enjoy socializing with your close circle of friends, you may find too much interaction draining and need some time alone to recoup.

fields.name: Operator
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ISTP, you are flexible and versatile, usually willing to roll with the punches. You most likely enjoy figuring out how things work and, to do this effectively, you want your own space. Because you are a hands-on learner, when solving problems, you probably like to use trial-and-error to find a solution. Your coworkers may observe you to be independent, self-reliant, and a practical problem solver.

You are naturally curious. As such, you probably enjoy tinkering with things and don’t mind exploring a variety of possible avenues, even though some of them may not work out. For you, experimentation is most likely fun. Given your inclination to explore when working on projects, you may have a tendency to follow your own path, even when others disagree.

<NAME/>, you like to live in the moment and have a knack for focusing on the here and now. You have the ability to hunker down and get lost in the moment. Your natural instinct, compared to others, is to act rather than philosophize. Thus, your colleagues most likely recognize you as someone who is resourceful and can cobble together available resources to create a usable solution.

Similar to other ISTPs, you like to work independently and enjoy doing your own thing. You have a willingness to jump into a problem without waiting for others and you probably prefer not to be tied down to people or systems as this may restrict your choices. As such, when coworkers suggest ideas to you or provide you with input, you may ignore their ideas in favor of your own.

You likely strive for efficiency. This approach can impact how you interact with others In particular, you probably don’t waste energy by censoring yourself. Additionally, you may be more willing to disregard social norms than your colleagues. While your coworkers may perceive you, at times, to be inappropriate or a little rough, you are likely trying to preserve your mental energy for things that require deeper attention and concentration.

Within your work, you’d probably rather focus on objective judgments. Therefore, you likely don’t get caught up in subjective and emotional conclusions. You may have a tendency to detach from things – people, emotions, places – without experiencing much stress. Therefore, rather than getting too personally connected, you most likely deal with problems in an impersonal manner, allowing you to attend to the necessary details, data, and facts.

<NAME/>, like others with the ISTP type, your present-mindedness allows you to be adaptable, inquisitive, and independent. As a result, your coworkers most likely see your greatest contributions to the workplace as your willingness to take things as they come, your desire to practically and logically figure out problems, and your inclination to take matters into your own hands.
fields.text_short: ISTPs are quiet and reserved, cool observers of life, usually interested in the how and why of things, and don’t waste personal energy.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ISTP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ISTPs, you tend to be fast moving, so if things slow to a steady, predictable pace, you may feel antsy or bored. Therefore, you may have trouble sticking to long-term endeavors, and you may find that you start more projects than you finish. 

Furthermore, you tend to be quite logical, to the point where you may not attend to, or even recognize, others’ feelings. You probably have some difficulty expressing your emotions, and it may be hard for others to interpret where you’re coming from. At times, you may be dubbed as overly private or even insensitive. In fact, you can become quite stubborn and blunt, especially when criticized, and you may not realize the effect your actions have on others.  

Finally, you may have trouble making commitments. You tend to live in the moment, so you don’t want to feel like you’re locked in to anything. You’re probably always ready to change course and willing to take a risk, which likely makes you a terrific troubleshooter. However, it can also lead you to make impulsive or irresponsible decisions at times.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Being dubbed as “loners” or “insensitive” may be one way ISTPs are misperceived. In part, this may be because you sometimes miscalculate other people’s feelings and struggle with certain social boundaries and expectations. You happen to be quiet, composed, and private, but you’re also prone to unpredictable bouts of enthusiasm and spontaneity. While you may have unorthodox ways of going about a task, your main concern is getting the job done and attaining an immediate payoff. Consequently, you don’t expend much energy getting others involved. It’s not that you don’t value others or think them capable, it’s just easier and faster to do it yourself. 

At the extreme, ISTPs may also be called “devil’s advocate,” when that’s probably not their intention at all. Just when people have reached a consensus, you may be the one to change positions or point out a contradiction. However, this isn’t because you’re trying to stir up trouble. You’re a logical problem-solver, and you’re also very flexible and willing to change your stance in the name of sound reason. Therefore, if you see an alternative point of view, you’ll bring it to attention.
