fields.name: Inventor
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ENTP, you are a visionary--able to clearly see an integrated future that is different from what currently exists. Your colleagues likely see you as quick-witted and clever. You probably prefer to focus on the big picture rather than getting bogged down in the details. Given your ability to remain open-minded, you most likely love the creative process and enjoy brainstorming and innovating.

 While big ideas and innovative suggestions come easily to you, you may struggle periodically implementing the ideas or you may lose interest in projects. Most likely, you’d much rather focus on all the possibilities than zero in on what is needed to maintain momentum on a project or attend to all the details.

 <NAME/>, some may describe you as the quintessential entrepreneur. In other words, you are open to risks, have a bias toward action, and enjoy connecting with other people. While you really like being around other people, you still have a strong independent streak. Most likely, new projects are frequently on your mind and you probably see unlimited opportunities in front of you, always willing to bite off more than you can chew. 

 Similar to other ENTPs, you probably love to debate with people, especially when quick thinking is called for. You like arguing for your position and are willing to challenge others. Logical debates on abstract topics may be particularly enjoyable for you. Along similar lines, you probably like negotiating and collaborating with people, as bouncing ideas off of others is important to you.

 When working with others, you tend to be straightforward, and this may occasionally be unsettling for others. Because of your challenging nature and focus on critical thinking, you may not attend to or be aware of how others receive your criticism or feedback, so you may not realize the impact you are having.

 Given your visionary, analytical, and critical way of thinking, you are probably prone to improvisation. You can get easily bored with routine and, therefore, can be dismissive of traditions and systems. Rather than planning or focusing on details, you most likely prefer to innovate for as long as you can. Likewise, you’ll keep your options open longer than most and act once you’ve considered a broad range of facts and data. You are happy to think through solutions in the moment and enjoy problem-solving your way around a roadblock.

 <NAME/>, like others with an ENTP type, you likely prefer the abstract and your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your ability to speculate, conceptualize, and create a vision for others. You challenge your peers to think critically and help to continuously generate new projects.
fields.text_short: ENTPs are creative thinkers, stimulating company, alert and outspoken, confident of their abilities, and can argue both sides of an issue.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ENTP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls.  

Like other ENTPs, you tend to be very rational and love a good debate. You’re intolerant of ideas that can’t be backed by logic, and you’re not shy about tearing them down. It’s probably not uncommon for you to provoke an argument, and if someone can’t withstand your commonsense scrutiny, you’ll not only dismiss the idea, but also the individual behind it.  

Furthermore, because you often overlook feelings, you may push arguments past people’s breaking points. To you, emotional points have little to no bearing, and you may be quite critical of people who consider such arguments to be valid. Especially when you’re wound up, you may talk over people forcefully and emphatically, and your tendency to be blunt and tactless may come across as insensitivity. While you can be quite charming, it may sometimes seem insincere. 

Finally, you may find it difficult to focus on one thing. You tend to be very flexible and always interested in the next best thing, so you may adapt and re-adapt, dropping good, solid plans when your excitement wanes. Because you don’t want to miss out on any new, shiny opportunities, you may jump ship often without following through. Consequently, you may come across as undependable and impulsive.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Being dubbed as “condescending” may be one way ENTPs are misperceived. You probably enjoy a good debate, and it’s likely that you have strong opinions that you’re ready to defend. However, at times, your passionate delivery may come across the wrong way. It’s not your intent to patronize, but rather, you have a strong desire to keep learning and get excited when someone presents you with a worthy challenge. It probably doesn’t even occur to you that not many have the confidence you do when facing confrontation. 

At times, ENTPs may be seen as “know-it-alls.” This may be because you sometimes cut people off during conversation, often finishing their thoughts for them. But this is only because you become animated at the prospect of an intellectual discussion. Your aim probably isn’t to dominate the conversation or assert your own beliefs. Rather, you’re eager to keep the dialogue going and get as much said as possible without being cut short.

fields.name: Expeditor
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ESTP, you are adventurous and bold, often looking for ways to push the boundaries and break out of the status quo. You like to keep things active, exciting, and novel. The mundane is not for you. Within the workplace, your colleagues appreciate the level of energy you bring to both your work and the work environment as well as the knack that you have for generating new ideas and keeping things fresh. You’ll seek out new opportunities and make the most of what is given to you, always with a willingness to dive in head first.

You likely don’t require a lot of structure. You are flexible and can easily adapt to different situations and circumstances. Therefore, you probably thrive in a work environment that allows you to balance numerous tasks. Because of this, however, you may have a tendency to become distracted or bored when things become too organized or routine. 

<NAME/>, you are also practical and resourceful. You’ll find the quickest way to get something done. You’d rather act on a project and think through the solutions in the moment than take the time to carefully think through the steps ahead of time. You like to keep your options open, as this may help you find the simplest way to complete a task or project. In the workplace, you help others take action when they may be stuck overthinking a problem. 

Similar to other ESTPs, you like a crowd and can easily socialize with others. You don’t mind being the center of attention and taking the spotlight. In fact, you probably feel more energized when others are around compared to when you are by yourself. You have a natural ability to tell stories and captivate a crowd. Your colleagues most likely would describe you as highly sociable.

When working with others, you can be quite direct and candid with your opinions. You are able to push aside feelings and focus on objective facts. You love a good debate, especially one that requires everyone to think quickly. However, you may miss subtle cues from your colleagues that indicate they find your approach to be insensitive. A lot of this stems from your strong bias toward action. Because of your desire for progress, you present ideas in a firm and passionate manner. When collaborating with others, you have a skill for bringing logical arguments to the table. 

Given your bold nature, you’re most likely willing to bend the rules a bit more than your colleagues. Compared to your coworkers, you may have a rebellious streak and have no problem questioning authority. This may be particularly true when you see organizational rules and administrative chores as unnecessary or as limitations to your work. Rather than follow strict rules, you’d rather run with your gut instinct or impulses.

<NAME/>, like others with an ESTP style, you are likely bold, ambitious, and flexible, all of which can be beneficial in the workplace. Your coworkers most likely appreciate the risks you take, your fresh ideas, and your willingness to work with what’s given to you. Additionally, the level of energy you bring to the work environment is probably something that your colleagues greatly value.
fields.text_short: ESTPs are adaptable realists, highly observant, fun loving, go with the flow, and make the most of every situation.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ESTP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us.  As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls.  

Like other ESTPs, you’re more interested in action than conversation, preferring to live life in the fast lane. But in doing so, you may ignore the needs of others, neglecting to consider their perspectives as you push forward. While you’re probably quite likeable, even charming, you’re not always really in tune with people’s feelings and don’t often express your own. In fact, emotionally charged situations probably make you quite uncomfortable. So, when communicating with someone, you may absorb specific details while the person’s intent and other subtleties may be lost on you. And, to some, your tendency to be objective and blunt may come across as criticism or dislike.  

Furthermore, you generally look for the quick fix and may grow impatient with long-range solutions. Considering rules or consequences stifles your spontaneity, so you’ll probably brush these factors aside. Yet, to others, such behavior may come across as defiant or unscrupulous. 

Finally, you have a distaste for interpersonal problems and may ignore them. If you are frustrated with someone, you’re unlikely to bring it up, which can be exasperating for those who prefer to have an open dialogue about problems. Instead, you may have a tendency to let issues simmer below the surface and bubble to the top from time to time in passive-aggressive ways.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Being dubbed as “troublemakers” is one way ESTPs may be misperceived. At times, people may witness you ignoring authority or breaking the rules and think you’re just being difficult. But this isn’t the case at all. You are willing to break the rules, but not for the purpose of making mischief. Your purpose is to solve concrete problems, and you’ll likely sidestep any regulations or red tape that stands in your way. Pushing the boundaries is something you do well, but you do it to get the ball rolling, make new discoveries, and ultimately accomplish your goals. 

At the extreme, ESTPs may also be seen as “fickle” or “careless.” This may be because you tend to leave things until the last minute or even miss important meetings and deadlines when you get caught up in something else. However, this doesn’t mean you don’t care about your work. In fact, you’re probably quite serious about it. While you tend to be fun-loving and live in the moment, you likely work just as hard as you play. You’re drawn to action and fresh experiences, and you may often be the one to shed light on new opportunities that could advance the company. The mundane, day-to-day tasks, however, are likely best left to another.
fields.skills: Expediency,Improvising,Gift of gab,Negotiation,Dealing with challenges,High observance,Solving problems,Living in the moment

fields.name: Implementor
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ESTJ, you are driven and have a keen ability to focus on outcomes. As such, you know how to get results and seek closure on projects. Your no-nonsense approach is likely a key asset in helping you make consistent progress, reach goals, and finish work within deadlines. You are probably willing to keep things moving, accept challenges, and take a systematic approach to your work. Within the workplace, your colleagues probably appreciate the level of focus that you have and your willingness to put in your share of the work. 

You probably want things to be exact, clear, and concise. You meet deadlines, you thrive on having plans, and you focus on objective facts. As such, you probably have a dislike for ambiguity and don’t want to waste time considering details that won’t help you reach the end. When presented with work, you likely want clearly defined problems so that you can resolve them logically and in a timely manner. Likewise, when making requests of others, you make sure to set clear standards and are straightforward with your expectations. 

<NAME/>, you are systematic and efficient. Thus, you probably have a tendency to find the most linear, logical, and objective path to complete your work. This most likely comes from your reliance on well-defined systems and processes rather than untested or hypothetical approaches. Because of these tendencies, you may be suspicious of unproven ideas and good at finding flaws in details. At times, you may seem to have a detached focus on efficiency, with limited patience for coddling.

Similar to other ESTJs, you like to be in charge. You most likely don’t mind taking the lead on organizing a group or planning an event and you probably have no problem running things, making you a natural in a business setting. You bring order to chaos and make sure that plans fall into place. As a result, others may look for you to take charge and ensure that logistics are taken care of.

When working with others, you have high standards. You expect other people to be honest, hard-working, and competent. As such, you may judge others when they don’t live up to these standards. Additionally, your patience can be tested when working with people who are slow learners. Likewise, you may not have time for people who are lazy or dishonest. For you, these traits are probably seen as completely within someone’s control and, therefore, are a source of unnecessary delays and inefficiencies in your work. 

Given your driven nature, you are proactive in getting things started and finished. Compared to others, you don’t procrastinate. Most likely, if you say that you are going to get something done, you’ll dive in immediately. With that said, while you are efficient and quick to act, your focus on results and closure may cause you to miss things periodically.

<NAME/>, like others with an ESTJ style, being driven, realistic in your approach to work, and tackling the challenging problems serves you well in the workplace.You colleagues most likely appreciate the high standards that you set for yourself and others as well as your willingness to see things through to the end.
fields.text_short: ESTJs are practical and realistic, naturals in business and mechanics, get things done, like to run things, and have no time to waste.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ESTJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ESTJs, you are very organized and motivated to complete the task at hand. However, you may be so tuned in to what has to be done that you become inflexible or stubborn. If the needs of the situation shift, you may have trouble changing course. You’re more likely to just get on with it and push others to follow suit. At times, people may think you are being overly rigid or unreasonable. 

Furthermore, you likely have a strong belief in what is good, bad, right, wrong, appropriate, or inappropriate. Many times, there is little room to budge on these convictions. In your mind, you’re right, and anyone who functions outside of your personal expectations probably won’t be in your good favor, and you may not be shy about telling them so. Under extreme circumstances, you may come across as bossy or judgmental. 

Finally, while you value being part of a cohesive group and contributing to the common good, you may not always be in tune with other people’s feelings or particularly adept at expressing your own. As a consequence, you may be misperceived as uncaring or insensitive when, in fact, you actually care quite a bit and are particularly vulnerable to criticism. At the same time, because you tend to be objective and focus so much on facts, you may wind up inadvertently hurting others’ feelings.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Sometimes ESTJs may come across as “close-minded.” This may be because you prefer sticking to the facts and what’s known rather than what-ifs and the indefinite. However, just because you prefer the predictable doesn’t mean you’re closed off to new ideas. You’ll keep an eye out for the best way to do things, but in the interest of consistency and saving time, you’ll probably steer toward a tried-and-true method. 

At the extreme, ESTJs may sometimes be dubbed as “pushy,” which isn’t their intention at all. Since you have high standards, you likely strive to motivate others to be productive so that your endeavors and projects will succeed. While your goal is to meet regulations and keep a sense of order, there are times when some people may feel bossed around or think you’ve overstepped your bounds. However, you believe in efficiency, and you’ve got a go-getter attitude that impels others to get the job done.
fields.skills: Taking charge,Being organized,Following through,Leadership,Remaining enthusiastic,Being punctual,Staying objective,Efficiency
fields.careers: Attorney,Business administrator,Financial officer,Insurance agent,Office manager,Project manager,Stockbroker,Underwriter

fields.name: Provider
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ESFJ, you are likely socially dynamic and love connecting with people. Being around others gives you energy. Your tendency to get involved with others coupled with your fast-paced nature may lead you to jump into problems quickly. You don’t like to sit around waiting. 

You have a knack for taking initiative, especially when it involves planning programs, making arrangements, and organizing social events. You’re probably great at getting people together and serving as the host. Given your ability to organize others, you want to be kept in the loop so that you’re aware when plans change. And because a good chunk of your self-worth can come from your connection with others, you may go out of your way to earn their appreciation.

<NAME/>, you’re a provider. In the workplace, you most likely feel the responsibility to not only help newcomers feel at home but also put in the time and energy necessary to provide for the group. In a similar light, you enjoy the consultant’s role, gladly offering advice or assistance. Colleagues most likely see you as a good citizen within the workplace, as you typically want to make sure others are satisfied, comfortable, and enjoying themselves.

Similar to other ESFJs, you’re probably more of a cooperator rather than a competitor, and when it comes to projects, you prefer group tasks over working alone. Collaborating helps you focus on maintaining harmony within the workplace, keeps you connected with your coworkers, and allows you to know what is going on socially--three things that are probably essential to you. 

When working with others, particularly in stressful or conflict situations, you strive to maintain harmony. Conflict, most likely, makes you uncomfortable as you want to ensure that those around you are getting along. As such, when these stressful situations arise, you do your best to be tactful and diplomatic, not wanting to hurt another person’s feelings. On the other hand, you most likely feel compelled to speak your mind and not compromise your values. 

You probably also have a strong bias toward action. And because closure is so important to you, you’re inclined to jump right into solving a problem rather than waiting for other perspectives. If you see the opportunity to wrap up loose ends, you take it. The quick, proactive approach is much more your style than a slower, more thoughtful one. Given this tendency, however, you may not take the time to analyze ideas and experiences as deeply as some of your coworkers.

<NAME/>, as an ESFJ, in the workplace, you are likely sociable, enjoy being involved with others, and want to connect with both new and long-term colleagues. Your coworkers probably appreciate your willingness to work with them and enjoy doing group projects with you. You most likely make those around you feel welcomed, appreciated, and listened to.
fields.text_short: ESFJs are warm-hearted, active committee members, sociable, always doing something nice for others, and have strong value systems.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ESFJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ESFJs, having security and responsibility is valuable to you, and you tend to care about your social status and what other people think. This may make you quite sensitive to criticism. Indeed, your strong desire to be liked may cause you insecurities at times. Because you require a lot of positive affirmation, you may be prone to play the victim or fish for compliments, which could come across as somewhat needy. 

Furthermore, your desire to be in people’s good graces may cause you to give too much. Because you don’t want to disappoint people, you may have trouble saying no, and such self-sacrifice can overshadow your own needs. As a result, you may overextend yourself leading to eventual exhaustion. 

Finally, you tend to be so focused on what should be done and the appropriate procedure to follow that you may become quite upset when the situation appears ambiguous. You don’t typically look at new ways of doing things and may come across as inflexible or reluctant to improvise. This may be especially true when there is the potential for a lot of uncertainty.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Being dubbed as “insincere” may be one way others misperceive ESFJs. Because you likely have a strong need to make everyone happy, some people might think you’re just playing whatever role you have to in order to win their favor. However, this isn’t the case at all. You thoroughly enjoy socializing and making sure the people around you feel comfortable. It’s true that you may bend over backwards for others, but your sincerity is undeniable. 

Some people may also think of ESFJs as “inflexible.” This may be because you tend to hold strongly to tradition, but this is because you see the value in practiced methods and well-formed ideas. But just because you prefer to follow the tried and true instead of going rogue doesn’t mean you’re inflexible. Instead, it may just point to your preference for an orderly, structured environment.
fields.skills: Motivating others,Being punctual,Staying productive,Following routine,Being reliable,Attending to others,Organizing processes,Creating order

fields.name: Protector
fields.text:
<NAME/>, as an ISFJ, within the workplace you are probably recognized as modest and humble. You likely see your successes as for the good of the group and you have a willingness to keep plugging away on tasks in the background to help out your team. You rarely require a thank you for your efforts as you want others in the workplace to be happy and, because of this, having your contributions go overlooked may be a little more common than you would like.

You may have a tendency to take things personally. Rather than outwardly displaying when you are upset, however, you’re more likely to internalize your emotions. In a similar vein, when you have been mistreated by others, rather than quickly reacting, you are probably slow to complain. Given these tendencies, other people may not recognize how sensitive you can be to criticism or rudeness.

<NAME/>, you’re probably very conscientious and feel a strong pull to complete tasks not only when something needs to get done but also when you say you are going to get it done. Additionally, you’re dedicated to established procedures and deadlines, and, because of this, your colleagues feel that they can count on you. Compared to others, you have a knack for remembering small details, even about other people, and do better when you have the chance to plan ahead.

Similar to other ISFJs, you are most likely both empathetic and supportive, putting a priority on building deep friendships with others. For you, though, fewer close relationships are far preferable to many surface-level relationships. With others, you make it a priority to find ways to connect and perform small acts of kindness. Overall, you like to interact with others and look for relationships that are both stable and peaceful.

When working with others, you try hard to meet everyone’s expectations. And because you feel responsible to those around you, you’ll probably go out of your way to make others happy. You may, however, sometimes feel like you have the weight of the world on your shoulders, even while you’re downplaying the duties you’re taking on.

When it comes to change, you like having ample time to adjust; big, upcoming changes may stress you out a little. Similarly, when change does occur, it may take you more time than others to get accustomed to your new settings. When there is a lot going on, you may feel overwhelmed and, possibly, prone to sensory overload. Ultimately, this reflects your strong need for stability. Therefore, you may feel most at home in a quiet and controlled environment.

<NAME/>, like others with the ISFJ type, your humility, altruism, and supportive nature are things that bring great value to your workplace and to those who interact with you daily. Your appreciation for cooperative environments and your willingness to buckle down and do the work for the good of the team are likely assets that you bring to the workplace.
fields.text_short: ISFJs are quiet and conscientious, loyal and devoted workers, sympathetic listeners, very dependable, and real team players.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ISFJ, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ISFJs, you tend to be humble, often downplaying your success. Most likely, you’re more concerned with others than yourself, especially when it comes to those closest to you, and you’ll place their needs above your own. It’s probably quite difficult for you to say “no” to people, and all of this may cause you to become overloaded and to eventually burn out. 

Furthermore, you may be particularly sensitive to criticism, but, at times, you can be your own biggest faultfinder. If someone says something to you that really bothers you, you may hold your hurt feelings inside, which could lead to internal melancholy or pent-up resentment. You’re also sensitive to how others might feel, and you’re unlikely to confront or critique someone, even if it could really help them in some way. 

Finally, you don’t particularly like change and may be dubbed as “set in your ways,” even if you’re not vocal about it. If something is working, you see no reason to change it. You’re focused on creating stability, and you may continue with the procedures and traditions that are in place beyond their utility.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character.

Being a “goody two shoes” or a “yes man” may be misconceptions about ISFJs. While it’s true that you tend to follow the rules and are loyal to your superiors, it doesn’t mean you’re unwilling to stand up for yourself. While you stay on the straight and narrow partly to please others, you also do so because you have a strong conscience. Furthermore, you’re likely observant of the past and highly aware of the consequences of deviance. You aren’t a doormat; you just want to do the right thing and stay out of trouble.

At the extreme, ISFJs may be misperceived as “lacking depth,” when this isn’t the case at all. Since you tend to be quiet and obedient, you may often be overshadowed by others. However, you likely have very strong opinions, even if you don’t express them, and intense feelings, though you appreciate your privacy. While some people may regard you as just another friendly face or worker bee, what they miss is the profound complexity you possess inside.
fields.skills: Creating structure,Following schedules,Attending to details,Honoring commitments,Caretaking,Being compassionate,Efficiency,Persistence

fields.name: Advocate
fields.text:
<NAME/>, because you are an ENFP, you are outgoing, democratic, and participative. Being very perceptive of others’ motives, you tend to be interested in what’s going on around you. You probably want to inspire others as much as you want to be inspired, and you may have a contagious enthusiasm for “causes.”

Most likely, you are people-oriented and skilled at anything having to do with interacting. You may operate in a very personal way, seeking relationships and spending untold hours on interpersonal intrigues. At times, your concern for other people’s problems might draw you off task and you might become overwhelmed by your self-assigned responsibility of harmonizing the lives of others.

Integrity is likely very important to you, and your sometimes uncompromising values and needs may conflict with company policies. While you are very loyal, your loyalty goes to the people in the organization and not so much to the systems and procedures.

Like other ENFPs, you abhor a lack of caring and appreciate the “human side” of the enterprise. You likely have a strongly held belief that everyone is obligated to care for everyone else. Often identifying with others to the point of demonstrating perfect empathy, you seem to know just what a person needs in order to function better. This ability to identify so strongly with others may put some strain on your own identity at times. You can become so dedicated to supporting others that you put your own needs and wants second. It’s sometimes only later that you regret your impulsive generosity.

Your basic attitude is one of credulity, enthusiasm, and idealism. Since you usually expect goodness, you tend to see the potential in everyone and everything. Enthusiasm on your part is usually demonstrated with effusive expressions of intense emotions, and your optimism can be quite contagious. On the other hand, you may be rather disappointed when “reality” doesn’t measure up to your idealistic expectations.

Warmth, graciousness, and charm are likely natural aspects of your communication style. You tend to think with imagery, and you are particularly gifted in reporting and rephrasing events so they become more illuminating, interesting, and valuable. Furthermore, you are sensitive to the nuances and unspoken aspects of communication, and you are often focused on implications and hidden agendas. And, since you are so concerned with human needs, you also tend to be a superb listener. One of your greatest joys is getting lost in conversation with another person.

Having variety in what you do is important to you. You frequently invent new ways of doing things and are masterful at “spur of the moment” activities, especially when they involve interacting with people. As a result, you may become fragmented from wanting to do too many different things all at once and from being pulled in too many directions, seeking to please everyone.

<NAME/>, like others with the ENFP type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your warmth, enthusiasm, authenticity, capacity to inspire, and penchant for unveiling and disclosing information. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: ENFPs are warm and enthusiastic, charming and interesting, people-oriented, know everyone and all that’s going on, and have a can-do attitude.
fields.blind_spots:
As an ENFP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other ENFPs, you may find it difficult to stay focused on one activity or project for too long. You are likely interested in so many things that it’s hard to narrow them down. Often, you will zero in on a project only to abandon it when another shiny, new opportunity comes along. Following through may be difficult for you, so you’ll often start more things than you finish. Similarly, since you’re always open to new possibilities, you may have trouble committing to decisions and wind up leaving things until the last minute. 

Furthermore, you’re prone to improvisation and you tend to be quite impulsive. It’s not up your alley to do a lot of planning, which may lead you to jump to conclusions or make errors in judgment. You’re probably always thinking about what could be, sometimes overlooking the value of what’s actually in front of you. While you’re enthusiastic about your endeavors, you may not always be realistic. Mundane upkeep and detailed tasks may be best left to another. 

Finally, you may be a popular person for others to lean on. However, you sometimes get so caught up in helping others that you neglect your own needs and responsibilities. And since you may be overly concerned with being liked, criticism or disapproval may be very upsetting for you, giving way to defensive outbursts.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

ENFPs may sometimes be dubbed as “lazy” or “flighty.” This may be because you are constantly excited by new ideas and tend to flit from one project to the next. You’re a master at finding new ways to innovate and have an uncanny ability to jump between multiple projects at once with ease. While some people may incorrectly assume you’re directionless or disinterested, you’re often just on the hunt for a new discovery. And, when you’re passionate about something, you have no trouble honing in on what’s important. 

At the extreme, some people may think ENFPs are “manipulators.” It’s true that you can be very persuasive, but your intent isn’t malicious. You’re probably exceptional when it comes to communicating your feelings and ideas in a way that compels people to see things from your point of view. You may often find that you can motivate people into doing things or switching gears. However, you likely have a strong moral code, so you use your power of persuasiveness for good instead of evil. Your goal isn’t to manipulate, but to advocate for the common good.
fields.skills: Motivating others,Generating ideas,Giving compliments/praise,Interacting with people,Thinking abstractly,Empathizing,Adapting,Resourcefulness

fields.name: Designer
fields.text:
<NAME/>, because you are an INTP, you prefer to spend your time deep in thought. Your inner world is a lively place of ideas and theories. You’re probably happiest when solving complex problems, and if you aren’t given the opportunity to do so in your work, you may find others’ problems to fix. While you are happy working independently, you’re pragmatic and want to do whatever it takes to get the job done, including collaborating with others.

You tend to be future-oriented and an abstract thinker, making you an avid strategist. You relish the process of planning and designing, though you may get more enjoyment out of the planning than the doing since you want to avoid routine.

Social conventions and small talk may not be high on your priority list. Rather, you have a preference for logic and reasoning and may not be as comfortable handling emotional interpersonal situations.

Because you trust logical reasoning above all else, you may be turned off by exaggeration and overly emotional responses. Because of this, you might appear somewhat aloof or cold to some, but you are simply searching for the rationale behind decisions and approaches. To that end, you aren’t afraid to reject and challenge anything you believe has been inaccurately presented.

Though you may not leap to take the lead in every situation, you’re more likely to do so when you feel you have some authority. Given that you have an almost insatiable thirst for knowledge, you probably consider yourself an expert in certain areas.

Like other INTPs, you probably abhor redundancy and hesitate to state the obvious, so your communications are frequently terse and you may assume you are understood. On the other hand, when asked to explain something, you may become quite technical with many details and much complexity.  In fact, because you are a keen wordsmith, you are able to express with great precision exactly what you mean.

You love taking things apart and putting them back together, whether machinery, ideas, or processes. You expect things to be orderly and logical, and you don’t hesitate to question and go back to the drawing board, picking apart your own designs as much as others’. You are probably well-known for being skeptical, which may frustrate people at times.  But for you, it’s not personal; it’s just the most expedient way to achieve accuracy, correctness, and efficiency.

<NAME/>, like others with the INTP type, your most valuable contributions to the workplace may include your ability to solve complex problems, your tenacity for designing processes and systems, and your dedicated pursuit of accuracy. In fact, these are probably some of the qualities that others admire most about you.
fields.text_short: INTPs are reserved and objective, focused on ideas, skilled with hairsplitting logic, enjoy theoretical/scientific topics, and have strongly defined interests.
fields.blind_spots:
As an INTP, you have many assets, but you may also have some potential blind spots. These are the aspects of our personalities that we’re not even really aware of but that may seem quite obvious to the people around us. As is described below, many of our strengths have accompanying pitfalls. 

Like other INTPs, you tend to be reserved and private. Often, you’re so consumed with your own thoughts that you unintentionally ignore the human element and emotional side of things. You may overlook what’s really important to others, and yourself, if it’s subjective or seemingly illogical. Since you’re slow to respond to people’s feelings and express your own, you may be perceived as distant and unsympathetic. 

Furthermore, you take pride in your knowledge and thought process, which may result in your being condescending at times. You’re capable of very complex, theoretical ideas, but it may be challenging to translate such intricacies to others. You may wind up oversimplifying your thoughts and talking down to people, inadvertently insulting them. 

Finally, you’re likely driven by a desire to optimize every situation you’re involved in, to the point of perfectionism. You remain open to constant revisions and may have trouble committing to decisions because you want things to be just right. You may feel inadequate next to your own standards and second-guess yourself.  In fact, it’s probably not uncommon for you to hold up the entire show based on one inconsequential flaw.
fields.misunderstood:
Because we’re all so different, it’s not always easy for others to see the motivation behind our decisions and actions. We all dread the moment when we look at someone and realize they just don’t get us at all; they simply don’t understand where we’re coming from. And though it happens to everyone, it still feels a difficult cross to bear. Because deep down, we want people to understand and accept us, and certainly not to make incorrect assumptions about our character. 

Being dubbed as “harsh” may be one way INTPs are misperceived. You probably value honest and open critiques, believing that candid feedback is what improves your work and propels a project forward. However, some people are more sensitive to criticism than you are and may wind up feeling hurt when you give it to them straight. It certainly isn’t your objective to hurt anyone’s feelings. You simply want to have an open discussion about improvement. 

People may also think of INTPs as “aloof” or generally disinterested in getting to know them. It’s true that you spend a lot of your time reflecting and thinking through your own ideas; being outwardly social and gregarious is probably not your forte. However, this doesn’t mean that you don’t enjoy getting to know people, especially those with the same affinity for intellectual conversation.

I understand what typical blind spots are for a person with my type of personality, when collaborating in my team.
I understand well how to approach my teammates with a sensitive topic in a way that fits well with their different personalities.
To motivate my team members, I know exactly what to say, what aspects of a topic to stress, or what to do.
I understand how my team's different personalities can complement each other well, to enhance the team's output.
I understand what typical sources for frustration are for me, concerning collaborating.
I understand how to bring conflict to a successful outcome in different manners, depending who in my team I'm having conflict with.
I understand which kinds of different personalities are in my team.
A conflict trigger is anything that triggers stress or anxiety. I identify and manage my own conflict triggers to avoid miscues in my interactions with teammates.
I consider the different personality types when addressing misunderstandings and aligning expectations with teammates.
I am aware of how the different members of my team prefer to communicate.
I adjust how I share information when communicating with various personality types.
When working with teammates whose personality types differ from my own I feel certain that they act with the team's best interests at heart.
I communicate openly with my teammates and do not feel judged or uncomfortable.
I do not experience fear and anxiety when working with teammates with different personality types.
I leverage the personality strengths of my teammates to work together in a complementary way.
I use my awareness of my strengths, weaknesses, and blind spots to collaborate more effectively with teammates.
I motivate teammates with different personality types by pointing out specific components of a project that I know they find appealing.
I recognize all my teammates' contributions and accomplishments towards our team's goals.
Team awareness
fields.description: Everyone in the team knows what kinds of different types of personalities are in the team.

fields.title: Conflict solving ability
fields.description: Team members know how to bring conflict with another team member to a successful outcome, depending who in my team I'm having conlict with.

fields.title: Dealing with frustration
fields.description: You and the other team members are aware of what your individual typical sources of frustration are, concerning collaboration.

fields.title: Ability to synergize
fields.description: The team understands how its different personalities can complement each other well, to enhance the team's output.

fields.title: Motivation ability
fields.description: The people of your team know exactly exactly what to say, what aspects of a topic to stress, or what to do, in order to motivate a specific team member.

fields.title: Trust
fields.description: The team members understand how to approach each other with a sensitive topic in a way that fits well with the specific personality of that person.

fields.title: Dealing with blind spots
fields.description: You and the other team members understand what typical blind spots are for a person of their personality, related to collaboration.

fields.title: Conflict Management
fields.description: To what extent do you and other team members bring a conflict to a successful outcome? Some teammates might have different sources of frustration, conflict triggers and preferred ways to arrive at a resolution.

fields.title: Communication
fields.description: To what extent do you and your teammates sufficiently adjust your communication style, depending on whom you are talking to in the team?

fields.title: Trust
fields.description: To what extent do the team's members trust each other and feel they can communicate openly with one another?

fields.title: Awareness
fields.description: To what extent is the team aware of its members' strengths and weaknesses and uses this knowledge to complement each other and collaborate effectively?

fields.title: Motivation and Drive
fields.description: To what extent do team members recognize each other's contributions and accomplishments and know what to point out to motivate each other?

fields.name: Discover your type
fields.description: Complete the personality assessment

fields.name: Learn something new
fields.description: Watch 3 videos or interactive sessions

fields.name: Create a team
fields.description: Create a team with at least 3 members

fields.name: Gain insights on working with your teammates
fields.description: Compare your type with at least 2 of your teammates

fields.name: Get an overview of your team profile
fields.description: Visit any of your teams

fields.name: Learn whats behind each type
fields.description: Visit the Learn About Types page

fields.name: Explore the team activities
fields.description: Open the guidelines for any team activity

fields.name: Participate in a team activity
fields.description: You or any of your teammates schedules a team activity

fields.name: Finalize a team activity
fields.description: Give feedback about an activity that you had participated in

fields.name: Co-design your team manifesto
fields.description: Finalize the closing activity by providing feedback
